            <h3>Project Overview</h3>
            <p>
                In this project, I used <strong>AWS Elastic Beanstalk</strong> to deploy a 
                <strong>sample Tomcat application</strong>. Elastic Beanstalk automates provisioning, scaling, 
                and monitoring, allowing developers to focus on code while AWS manages infrastructure.
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Architecture -->
        <div class="project-section alt-bg">
            <h3>Architecture Explanation</h3>
            <p>Key components involved in this deployment:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Elastic Beanstalk</strong> – Service that orchestrates resources for app deployment.</li>
                <li><strong>EC2 Instance(s)</strong> – Run the Tomcat application.</li>
                <li><strong>Security Group</strong> – Controls inbound access (HTTP/SSH).</li>
                <li><strong>IAM Role</strong> – Grants EC2 instances permissions (e.g., AWSElasticBeanstalkWebTier).</li>
                <li><strong>Load Balancer (optional)</strong> – Distributes traffic in production setups.</li>
                <li><strong>CloudWatch</strong> – Monitors application health and logs.</li>
                <li><strong>User</strong> – Accesses the Tomcat app via public URL provided by Elastic Beanstalk.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Key Learnings -->
        <div class="project-section">
            <h3>Key Learnings</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Understood how Elastic Beanstalk abstracts infrastructure management.</li>
                <li>Configured IAM roles for Elastic Beanstalk environments.</li>
                <li>Learned how Beanstalk provisions EC2, Security Groups, and monitoring automatically.</li>
                <li>Experienced deploying an app without writing CloudFormation or Terraform code.</li>
                <li>Monitored health status and accessed app logs directly from Beanstalk.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Best Practices -->
        <div class="project-section alt-bg">
            <h3>Notes & Best Practices</h3>
            <p>
                While the lab deployed a sample app with default settings, production setups often require:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Custom domains with Route 53 and HTTPS certificates.</li>
                <li>Multiple Availability Zones with Auto Scaling for high availability.</li>
                <li>Dedicated database backend (Amazon RDS) instead of local DB.</li>
                <li>CI/CD integration with CodePipeline or GitHub Actions for automated deployments.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

